SIMPLE: inclusion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inclusion
<hw>In*clu"sion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>inclusio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>inclusion</ets>. See
<er>Include</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of including, or the state of being
included; limitation; restriction; <as>as, the lines of
<ex>inclusion</ex> of his policy</as>.</def> <rj><au>Sir W.
Temple.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Something that is included.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Min.)</fld> <def>A foreign substance, either liquid
or solid, usually of minute size, inclosed in the mass of a
mineral.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Biol., Cytology)</fld> <def>A small body suspended
within the cytoplasm of a cell.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Logic, Math.)</fld> <def>The relationship existing
between two sets if one is a subset of the other.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inclusive</ent>⟦br⟧
